(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
&amp;#123;&amp;#123;id name=&amp;#34;_GoBack&amp;#34;/}}(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1.2em&amp;#34; %)Methodology and In-Round Action

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)
**In order to have effective and fair energy conservation policy, we must restore identities, which have been excluded from the conversation, through actions and performances of resistance.**

* (((
(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**Agrawal and Gibson 1998 **(Arun and Clark, Professors at Yale University and Indiana University, “Enchantment and Disenchantment: The Role of Community in Natural Resource Conservation”)
)))

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)
\\**And to be able to engage in these acts and performances of resistance effectively, dominant social groups should reject and confront the systems of power/oppression from which they receive privilege by being allies.**

* (((
(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**Edwards** **2007** (Keith, Director of Campus Life at Macalester College, “Aspiring Social Justice Ally Identity Development)
)))

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)
\\**Methodology of becoming an ally**
**Bishop 2002** (Anne, Former Coordinator of Development education for Canadian University Services Overseas, “Becoming an Ally: Breaking the Cycle of Oppression-in People-“)
__**There are six steps in becoming an ally. They are:**__

(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**1.**            __** Understanding oppression, how it came about, how it is held in place, and how it stamps its pattern on the individuals and institutions that continuously recreate it;**__


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**2.**            __** Understanding different oppression, how they are similar, how they differ, and how they reinforce one another. The vast majority of us,**__** **however__** belong somewhere in between; we are oppressors in some parts of our identity and oppressed in others.**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**3.**            __**Consciousness and healing:**__

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**4.**            __**Becoming a worker in your own liberation**__
**Bishop 2002** (Anne, Former Coordinator of Development education for Canadian University Services Overseas, “Becoming an Ally: Breaking the Cycle of Oppression-in People-“)
(% style=&amp;#34;color:#000000;&amp;#34; %)__**Human liberation begins with breaking the silence, ending the shame, and sharing our concerns and feelings. Story-telling leads to analysis. Analysis leads to strategy. Strategy leads to action, together, to change the injustices we suffer. Action leads to another round of reflection, analysis, strategy, and action. This is the process of liberation.**__(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif; font-size: 1.2em&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**5.**            __**Becoming an ally**__ (The step is about taking direct action)

(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**Allied behavior is an effective way of interrupting the cycle of violence by breaking the silence that reinforces the cycle, and by promoting a new set of behavior through modeling and mentoring**

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)**Ayvazian 1995 **(Andrea, Former Dean of Religious Life and Protestant Chaplain at Mount Holyoke College “Interrupting the Cycle of Oppression: The Role of Allies as Agents of Change”)
\\

(% style=&amp;#34;margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)


(% style=&amp;#34;text-indent: -0.63in; margin-bottom: 0in&amp;#34; %)
(% style=&amp;#34;color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Times New Roman serif&amp;#34; %)6.            __**Maintaining Hope.**__ __**An effective social justice group**__, whatever its purpose,__** can only maintain its hope if a balance of these two ways **__(intellectual processes and fun__**) of functioning is established.**__ (Need for performance and acceptance argument). __**We also must have affirmation, acceptance, tolerance**__, pleasure, joy, humour, release, __**creativity, and fun. If there is too much intellectual work, participants burn out and lose hope. Too much intellectual work can also result in making judgments and distinctions within the group, with some members putting others down. On the other hand, if there is too much openness and fun, the group can be at risk of becoming confused and co-opted.**__

